WEBVTT

NOTE
This file was generated by Descript <www.descript.com>

00:00:05.480 --> 00:00:08.309
Hello, hello, hello, and welcome

00:00:08.310 --> 00:00:10.110
to English Learning for Curious

00:00:10.110 --> 00:00:13.080
Minds, by Leonardo English, the show

00:00:13.090 --> 00:00:14.830
where you can listen to fascinating

00:00:14.830 --> 00:00:17.310
stories and learn weird and wonderful

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:19.350
things about the world at the same

00:00:19.350 --> 00:00:21.119
time as improving your English.

00:00:21.650 --> 00:00:23.980
I'm Alastair Budge, and today

00:00:24.190 --> 00:00:26.700
it's part three of our three-part

00:00:26.730 --> 00:00:29.520
mini-series on the theme of animals.

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:31.810
In part one, we learned about

00:00:31.810 --> 00:00:34.500
man's best friend, the loyal dog.

00:00:34.929 --> 00:00:36.840
In part two, we explored

00:00:36.860 --> 00:00:38.439
the enigmatic cat.

00:00:38.820 --> 00:00:41.390
And today, in part three, we're

00:00:41.500 --> 00:00:43.210
going to talk about an animal

00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:45.220
that never existed at all.

00:00:45.450 --> 00:00:46.199
The dragon.

00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:49.060
OK then, let's not waste a

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:51.549
minute and get right into it.

00:00:52.660 --> 00:00:55.460
Imagine you're a peasant farmer in

00:00:55.460 --> 00:00:58.599
medieval England, around the year 1200.

00:00:59.420 --> 00:01:01.110
You've never travelled more

00:01:01.110 --> 00:01:02.720
than a few kilometres from the

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:04.009
village where you were born.

00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:05.480
You can't read.

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:07.110
You've never seen a map.

00:01:07.539 --> 00:01:09.940
You have little idea what lies beyond

00:01:09.950 --> 00:01:12.350
the forest at the edge of your world.

00:01:12.850 --> 00:01:15.030
But you know, with absolute

00:01:15.030 --> 00:01:17.890
certainty, that dragons exist.

00:01:18.760 --> 00:01:20.740
You know they're serpentine

00:01:20.740 --> 00:01:23.390
creatures with scales like armour.

00:01:24.230 --> 00:01:25.810
You know they breathe fire.

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:27.900
You know they often

00:01:27.910 --> 00:01:30.070
hoard treasure in caves.

00:01:30.599 --> 00:01:32.839
You know that knights sometimes

00:01:32.860 --> 00:01:35.960
hunt them, and that slaying a dragon

00:01:36.220 --> 00:01:38.300
is the ultimate test of courage.

00:01:39.020 --> 00:01:41.880
And in fact, just 150 years later,

00:01:42.290 --> 00:01:44.730
your country, England, would make

00:01:44.750 --> 00:01:47.350
a dragon slayer its patron saint.

00:01:48.389 --> 00:01:51.780
Now, imagine you're a scholar in Song

00:01:51.850 --> 00:01:54.419
Dynasty China, at a similar time.

00:01:55.190 --> 00:01:56.560
You live thousands of

00:01:56.560 --> 00:01:57.700
kilometres from England.

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:00.950
Your civilisation has had no meaningful

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:03.380
contact with Europe, and will not

00:02:03.389 --> 00:02:05.789
do so for several hundred years.

00:02:06.630 --> 00:02:08.280
You too have never

00:02:08.280 --> 00:02:09.659
travelled far from home.

00:02:10.430 --> 00:02:12.780
But like the English peasant

00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:14.520
on the other side of the world,

00:02:14.990 --> 00:02:17.440
you know that dragons exist.

00:02:18.570 --> 00:02:21.110
For you, they are slightly different.

00:02:21.849 --> 00:02:24.010
They are still long, serpentine

00:02:24.010 --> 00:02:25.430
creatures with scales.

00:02:25.839 --> 00:02:28.789
But their bodies are longer, they

00:02:28.789 --> 00:02:31.090
don’t have wings, and they live

00:02:31.100 --> 00:02:34.000
in rivers and seas, not caves.

00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:36.910
And they don’t typically breathe

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:40.350
fire, but they do have magical powers.

00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:44.710
In your culture, dragons control

00:02:44.719 --> 00:02:46.859
the weather and bring rain.

00:02:47.450 --> 00:02:49.170
They represent imperial

00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:51.140
power and ancient wisdom.

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:54.340
And you certainly wouldn’t dream

00:02:54.340 --> 00:02:57.380
of killing one – for you, dragons

00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:01.040
are benevolent, helpful and wise.

00:03:02.030 --> 00:03:05.070
But both you and the English peasant

00:03:05.299 --> 00:03:07.130
are thinking of fundamentally

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:09.040
the same type of creature.

00:03:10.490 --> 00:03:13.070
And it's not just England and China.

00:03:13.530 --> 00:03:15.500
Medieval Wales had dragons.

00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:17.270
So did ancient Greece.

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:18.310
And Rome.

00:03:18.670 --> 00:03:19.400
And India.

00:03:19.549 --> 00:03:20.249
And Japan.

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:21.340
And Vietnam.

00:03:21.449 --> 00:03:22.349
And the Vikings.

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:23.969
And the Slavic peoples.

00:03:24.110 --> 00:03:25.839
And pre-Columbian Mexico.

00:03:26.610 --> 00:03:29.570
Nearly every human culture, across every

00:03:29.570 --> 00:03:32.059
continent, across thousands of years of

00:03:32.059 --> 00:03:35.410
history, has some version of the dragon.

00:03:36.530 --> 00:03:39.500
And this is one of the most remarkable

00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:42.140
patterns in all of mythology:

00:03:42.550 --> 00:03:44.860
almost every civilisation has

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:48.010
independently decided dragons existed,

00:03:48.460 --> 00:03:50.989
despite no evidence they ever did.

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:54.470
And today, we're going to talk about

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:57.329
some of the theories as to why.

00:03:58.579 --> 00:04:01.180
Let's start by taking a mini tour of

00:04:01.180 --> 00:04:03.800
dragons around the world, because while

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:06.718
they share some common features, they are

00:04:06.810 --> 00:04:10.050
fascinatingly different in their details.

00:04:10.500 --> 00:04:13.400
And this might give us a few

00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:15.719
clues about their origins.

00:04:17.007 --> 00:04:20.557
In China, the dragon—or lóng in

00:04:20.557 --> 00:04:23.377
Mandarin—is one of the most important

00:04:23.387 --> 00:04:25.537
symbols in the entire culture.

00:04:26.307 --> 00:04:29.417
It's a creature of water and weather,

00:04:29.887 --> 00:04:33.717
associated with rain, rivers, and the sea.

00:04:35.077 --> 00:04:37.307
It's typically depicted as an

00:04:37.317 --> 00:04:40.197
enormously long, serpentine creature

00:04:40.327 --> 00:04:43.287
with four legs, antler-like horns,

00:04:43.447 --> 00:04:47.297
and a somewhat feline, cat-like face.

00:04:48.437 --> 00:04:50.587
Crucially, Chinese dragons

00:04:51.077 --> 00:04:53.297
don't usually have wings.

00:04:53.867 --> 00:04:56.307
They fly anyway, through some

00:04:56.307 --> 00:04:58.227
kind of supernatural power.

00:04:59.377 --> 00:05:02.587
And unlike Western dragons, Chinese

00:05:02.597 --> 00:05:05.767
dragons are generally benevolent.

00:05:06.177 --> 00:05:08.237
They bring rain to farmers.

00:05:08.557 --> 00:05:11.107
They represent wisdom and power.

00:05:11.827 --> 00:05:13.277
They were the symbol of the emperor

00:05:13.277 --> 00:05:16.247
himself—the emperor sat on the

00:05:16.257 --> 00:05:19.347
Dragon Throne, wore robes embroidered

00:05:19.347 --> 00:05:21.677
with dragons, and was sometimes

00:05:21.677 --> 00:05:23.677
called the "son of the dragon."

00:05:25.047 --> 00:05:27.357
To kill a dragon in Chinese

00:05:27.357 --> 00:05:29.837
mythology would be unthinkable.

00:05:30.657 --> 00:05:33.137
You might seek the favour of a dragon,

00:05:33.457 --> 00:05:36.267
or fear its wrath if you angered it,

00:05:36.767 --> 00:05:39.687
but dragons were fundamentally good,

00:05:40.137 --> 00:05:43.027
or at least neutral forces of nature.

00:05:44.241 --> 00:05:47.491
And this concept of the benevolent dragon

00:05:47.911 --> 00:05:50.671
is one we see spread throughout East Asia.

00:05:51.571 --> 00:05:54.431
In Japan, the dragon is called ryū,

00:05:54.991 --> 00:05:57.431
and it's very similar to the Chinese

00:05:57.451 --> 00:06:01.481
version—a sort of water deity, a bringer

00:06:01.481 --> 00:06:04.121
of rain, associated with the sea.

00:06:05.251 --> 00:06:07.691
In Korea, it's called yong.

00:06:07.801 --> 00:06:09.491
In Vietnam, rồng.

00:06:10.521 --> 00:06:13.671
All serpentine, like snakes, all

00:06:13.721 --> 00:06:16.061
powerful, all connected to water.

00:06:17.451 --> 00:06:20.431
Now, European dragons, as you will

00:06:20.441 --> 00:06:22.811
probably know, were very different.

00:06:23.801 --> 00:06:26.381
In medieval European mythology,

00:06:26.691 --> 00:06:30.221
dragons were almost uniformly evil.

00:06:30.741 --> 00:06:33.701
They were destroyers, not protectors.

00:06:33.991 --> 00:06:36.121
They breathed fire, not water.

00:06:36.631 --> 00:06:39.731
They hoarded gold and treasure in caves,

00:06:40.091 --> 00:06:42.441
jealously guarding it from humans.

00:06:42.981 --> 00:06:46.121
They kidnapped princesses, demanded virgin

00:06:46.121 --> 00:06:49.061
sacrifices, and terrorised villages.

00:06:50.411 --> 00:06:54.291
And their role, their purpose, and

00:06:54.291 --> 00:06:56.501
what almost always happens to a dragon

00:06:56.501 --> 00:06:59.831
in a story, was to be slain, killed

00:07:00.061 --> 00:07:02.581
by some kind of brave warrior; they

00:07:02.581 --> 00:07:05.001
were a threat to be extinguished.

00:07:06.801 --> 00:07:09.381
In terms of its appearance, the

00:07:09.421 --> 00:07:12.011
classic European dragon typically

00:07:12.211 --> 00:07:15.051
had four legs and two wings.

00:07:15.561 --> 00:07:18.401
It was reptilian, covered in

00:07:18.501 --> 00:07:21.301
impenetrable scales, often with a

00:07:21.311 --> 00:07:23.371
long tail it could use as a weapon.

00:07:24.461 --> 00:07:26.741
Its breath was its most dangerous

00:07:26.741 --> 00:07:29.781
feature: fire, of course, flames

00:07:29.971 --> 00:07:31.551
that could incinerate a knight

00:07:31.821 --> 00:07:33.761
even when wearing full armour.

00:07:34.954 --> 00:07:36.534
We see this type of dragon

00:07:36.644 --> 00:07:38.484
throughout European mythology.

00:07:39.524 --> 00:07:42.844
In the Old English epic Beowulf, the

00:07:42.854 --> 00:07:45.944
hero faces a dragon in his final battle.

00:07:46.604 --> 00:07:49.154
The dragon has been sleeping on a hoard

00:07:49.154 --> 00:07:51.514
of treasure for three hundred years.

00:07:52.274 --> 00:07:55.384
When a thief steals a single cup from

00:07:55.384 --> 00:07:58.314
the hoard, the dragon wakes in fury

00:07:58.604 --> 00:08:00.744
and begins burning the countryside.

00:08:01.574 --> 00:08:04.374
Beowulf kills the dragon, but is

00:08:04.384 --> 00:08:06.364
mortally wounded in the process.

00:08:07.354 --> 00:08:09.844
In Germanic mythology, the hero

00:08:09.884 --> 00:08:12.814
Siegfried kills the dragon Fafnir,

00:08:12.814 --> 00:08:14.644
who guards a cursed treasure.

00:08:15.334 --> 00:08:17.274
He then proceeds to bathe

00:08:17.431 --> 00:08:18.594
in the dragon's blood.

00:08:19.254 --> 00:08:22.331
In Greek mythology, dragons, or large

00:08:22.331 --> 00:08:25.054
serpents, appear throughout the legends,

00:08:25.324 --> 00:08:28.224
from Apollo killing the Python to

00:08:28.284 --> 00:08:31.054
Heracles fighting the many-headed Hydra.

00:08:32.014 --> 00:08:34.154
And in the Christian tradition,

00:08:34.544 --> 00:08:36.844
dragons became explicitly

00:08:36.854 --> 00:08:39.294
associated with evil and Satan.

00:08:39.954 --> 00:08:41.924
The Book of Revelation describes

00:08:41.924 --> 00:08:44.604
Satan as a great red dragon

00:08:44.644 --> 00:08:47.144
with seven heads and ten horns.

00:08:47.694 --> 00:08:50.004
Saint George, the patron saint of

00:08:50.004 --> 00:08:52.174
England, is famous for slaying a

00:08:52.184 --> 00:08:54.454
dragon that was terrorising a town

00:08:54.644 --> 00:08:56.554
and demanding human sacrifices.

00:08:57.464 --> 00:08:59.064
The dragon in Christian

00:08:59.064 --> 00:09:01.644
symbolism represented paganism,

00:09:01.964 --> 00:09:04.094
chaos, the devil himself.

00:09:04.834 --> 00:09:08.274
To slay a dragon was to defeat evil.

00:09:09.564 --> 00:09:11.124
But dragons weren't

00:09:11.124 --> 00:09:13.174
confined to Asia and Europe.

00:09:13.954 --> 00:09:17.154
In Mesoamerica, the Aztec and Maya

00:09:17.414 --> 00:09:20.424
worshipped Quetzalcoatl, the feathered

00:09:20.464 --> 00:09:23.814
serpent, a dragon-like deity associated

00:09:23.954 --> 00:09:25.994
with wind, air, and learning.

00:09:26.804 --> 00:09:29.594
And similar creatures appear in

00:09:29.934 --> 00:09:31.914
Aboriginal Australian mythology,

00:09:32.094 --> 00:09:34.774
ancient Egypt, Mesopotamian mythology,

00:09:34.994 --> 00:09:37.034
and ancient Norse mythology.

00:09:37.454 --> 00:09:39.574
Nearly every culture has one.

00:09:40.324 --> 00:09:41.544
They're almost always

00:09:41.844 --> 00:09:44.234
serpentine or reptilian.

00:09:44.634 --> 00:09:45.604
They're almost always

00:09:45.704 --> 00:09:47.354
ancient and powerful.

00:09:48.084 --> 00:09:49.614
They're frequently associated

00:09:49.854 --> 00:09:52.504
with water—rivers, seas,

00:09:52.934 --> 00:09:55.344
rain, the primordial ocean.

00:09:56.024 --> 00:09:59.564
They often represent chaos, or primordial

00:09:59.574 --> 00:10:02.784
forces, or the power of nature itself.

00:10:03.854 --> 00:10:06.964
So the question remains:  why?

00:10:07.844 --> 00:10:10.814
Why did humans, independently, across

00:10:10.874 --> 00:10:13.404
thousands of kilometres and thousands

00:10:13.404 --> 00:10:16.404
of years, all imagine similar creatures?

00:10:17.394 --> 00:10:20.624
Well, there are several theories, some

00:10:20.634 --> 00:10:22.854
of them more plausible than others.

00:10:24.334 --> 00:10:26.984
The first and most obvious explanation

00:10:27.354 --> 00:10:29.214
is the one you may know already,

00:10:29.514 --> 00:10:32.024
or might be able to hazard a guess:

00:10:32.664 --> 00:10:35.564
ancient people found dinosaur fossils.

00:10:36.734 --> 00:10:39.064
This theory has been around for a

00:10:39.064 --> 00:10:42.614
while, and it makes intuitive sense.

00:10:43.654 --> 00:10:46.264
Dinosaur bones have of course existed

00:10:46.294 --> 00:10:48.794
for all of human history, but it

00:10:48.794 --> 00:10:51.274
wasn't until the 19th century that

00:10:51.274 --> 00:10:53.284
humans understood what they were.

00:10:54.574 --> 00:10:58.054
So, imagine you’re a shepherd in ancient

00:10:58.064 --> 00:11:01.244
Greece and while digging a well for your

00:11:01.254 --> 00:11:04.214
village, you uncover an enormous skull

00:11:04.524 --> 00:11:07.824
with a large snout and teeth like daggers.

00:11:09.144 --> 00:11:11.454
Perfectly understandably, your first

00:11:11.454 --> 00:11:13.694
reaction might be that you’ve found the

00:11:13.694 --> 00:11:16.564
remains of some kind of reptilian beast.

00:11:16.944 --> 00:11:18.234
A terrifying monster.

00:11:18.804 --> 00:11:19.384
A dragon.

00:11:20.504 --> 00:11:22.924
And we know this happened because we

00:11:22.924 --> 00:11:25.144
have historical records of ancient

00:11:25.154 --> 00:11:27.934
people finding fossils and interpreting

00:11:27.934 --> 00:11:30.084
them as mythological creatures.

00:11:31.394 --> 00:11:33.994
The ancient Greeks found large fossils

00:11:34.014 --> 00:11:37.224
in quarries and mines and interpreted

00:11:37.224 --> 00:11:40.764
them as evidence of giants and monsters.

00:11:42.194 --> 00:11:45.104
In China, fossilised bones have been

00:11:45.104 --> 00:11:47.004
used in traditional medicine for

00:11:47.114 --> 00:11:49.364
thousands of years, where they're

00:11:49.364 --> 00:11:52.414
still called "dragon bones"—lóng gǔ.

00:11:53.244 --> 00:11:56.134
Even today, you can go to traditional

00:11:56.174 --> 00:11:58.614
Chinese medicine shops and buy

00:11:58.844 --> 00:12:01.034
powdered "dragon bone," which is

00:12:01.034 --> 00:12:03.554
actually fossilised animal remains,

00:12:03.924 --> 00:12:06.014
usually from Ice Age mammals.

00:12:07.314 --> 00:12:10.374
The ancient Chinese clearly found these

00:12:10.374 --> 00:12:13.734
bones, and attributed them to dragons.

00:12:14.944 --> 00:12:17.404
So fossils were definitely

00:12:17.524 --> 00:12:18.904
part of the inspiration.

00:12:19.534 --> 00:12:22.204
But here's the problem: fossils

00:12:22.254 --> 00:12:24.374
alone don't explain all the

00:12:24.384 --> 00:12:26.424
specific features of dragons.

00:12:27.124 --> 00:12:29.714
No fossil breathes fire.

00:12:29.824 --> 00:12:31.944
No fossil hoards gold.

00:12:32.224 --> 00:12:35.384
No fossil has wings and four legs.

00:12:36.294 --> 00:12:39.224
Fossils might explain why ancient people

00:12:39.524 --> 00:12:42.404
believed in large, extinct reptiles.

00:12:42.761 --> 00:12:46.114
But they don't fully explain why

00:12:46.164 --> 00:12:48.124
those reptiles, across different

00:12:48.124 --> 00:12:50.554
cultures, all had such similar

00:12:50.814 --> 00:12:53.841
supernatural abilities and behaviours.

00:12:54.714 --> 00:12:57.404
For that, we need to look deeper.

00:12:58.074 --> 00:13:00.714
And this brings us to theory number

00:13:00.714 --> 00:13:03.354
two, which is perhaps a little more out

00:13:03.354 --> 00:13:06.874
there, controversial and implausible,

00:13:06.934 --> 00:13:09.024
but worth mentioning in any case.

00:13:09.544 --> 00:13:12.924
And that’s that dragons somehow represent

00:13:12.954 --> 00:13:15.644
our deepest, most ancient fears.

00:13:16.724 --> 00:13:19.444
Specifically, dragons might be a

00:13:19.484 --> 00:13:22.104
combination of the predators that hunted

00:13:22.104 --> 00:13:24.534
our ancestors for millions of years,

00:13:24.874 --> 00:13:28.624
and that somehow, somewhere in our DNA

00:13:28.814 --> 00:13:32.354
is hardwired this primordial fear of

00:13:32.354 --> 00:13:34.844
the various predators that pursued us.

00:13:35.864 --> 00:13:36.894
Think about it this way.

00:13:37.544 --> 00:13:40.534
For most of human evolutionary history—so

00:13:40.804 --> 00:13:42.544
going back hundreds of thousands of

00:13:42.544 --> 00:13:45.404
years—our early ancestors lived in

00:13:45.454 --> 00:13:48.294
constant fear of being killed and eaten.

00:13:49.464 --> 00:13:51.824
And the predators that ate us

00:13:52.204 --> 00:13:54.894
fell into three main categories.

00:13:55.824 --> 00:13:58.024
First: large snakes.

00:13:58.504 --> 00:14:00.734
Venomous snakes and constricting

00:14:00.734 --> 00:14:03.154
pythons killed our ancestors.

00:14:03.774 --> 00:14:06.324
Even today, humans have an

00:14:06.364 --> 00:14:08.114
instinctive fear of snakes.

00:14:08.744 --> 00:14:11.854
Children as young as six months old show

00:14:11.894 --> 00:14:14.654
fear responses to snake images, even

00:14:14.654 --> 00:14:16.364
if they've never seen a snake before.

00:14:17.304 --> 00:14:20.464
This fear is hardwired into our brains

00:14:20.474 --> 00:14:23.534
through millions of years of evolution.

00:14:24.834 --> 00:14:27.164
Second: large cats.

00:14:28.084 --> 00:14:29.454
Leopards, in particular,

00:14:29.804 --> 00:14:31.374
were among the most dangerous

00:14:31.384 --> 00:14:33.574
predators early humans faced.

00:14:34.154 --> 00:14:36.264
They're ambush predators.

00:14:36.364 --> 00:14:38.304
They're incredibly strong.

00:14:38.404 --> 00:14:41.224
They drag their prey into trees.

00:14:42.264 --> 00:14:44.754
Fossil evidence shows that leopards

00:14:45.114 --> 00:14:47.154
hunted our ancestors regularly.

00:14:47.974 --> 00:14:50.564
We evolved an instinctive fear of

00:14:50.564 --> 00:14:53.744
their eyes, their fangs, their roar.

00:14:54.994 --> 00:14:57.504
And thid: large birds of prey.

00:14:58.404 --> 00:15:01.474
Eagles and hawks could snatch children.

00:15:02.284 --> 00:15:04.054
Even today, raptors will

00:15:04.094 --> 00:15:06.344
occasionally attack small humans.

00:15:07.414 --> 00:15:09.444
Our ancestors would have feared

00:15:09.484 --> 00:15:11.374
attack from above, feared

00:15:11.604 --> 00:15:14.014
talons and beaks and wings.

00:15:15.094 --> 00:15:18.984
Now, here's the theory: what if the dragon

00:15:19.044 --> 00:15:23.124
is a synthesis, a mixture, of all three?

00:15:24.264 --> 00:15:26.274
A dragon has the body of a

00:15:26.274 --> 00:15:29.584
snake—long, serpentine, scaled.

00:15:29.834 --> 00:15:31.864
It has the roar and the fierce,

00:15:31.864 --> 00:15:34.054
predatory nature of a big cat.

00:15:34.764 --> 00:15:36.994
It has the wings and the ability to

00:15:36.994 --> 00:15:39.684
attack from above like a bird of prey.

00:15:40.624 --> 00:15:42.834
It's the ultimate predator, combining

00:15:42.894 --> 00:15:45.494
everything our ancestors feared most.

00:15:46.694 --> 00:15:47.784
Some evolutionary

00:15:47.784 --> 00:15:50.037
psychologists go even further.

00:15:50.688 --> 00:15:53.534
They suggest that humans might have

00:15:53.534 --> 00:15:56.024
a kind of deep evolutionary memory,

00:15:56.414 --> 00:15:59.194
not of dinosaurs per se, as humans

00:15:59.224 --> 00:16:01.414
never lived alongside dinosaurs, but

00:16:01.714 --> 00:16:04.294
of large reptilian predators like

00:16:04.384 --> 00:16:07.124
crocodiles and monitor lizards, which

00:16:07.274 --> 00:16:10.294
absolutely did coexist with early humans.

00:16:11.234 --> 00:16:14.094
Crocodiles are ancient, terrifying,

00:16:14.104 --> 00:16:16.274
and nearly impossible to kill.

00:16:16.894 --> 00:16:20.004
They lurk in water and explode

00:16:20.024 --> 00:16:22.994
into sudden, devastating violence.

00:16:23.504 --> 00:16:25.994
They're basically living dragons.

00:16:27.044 --> 00:16:29.174
And here's what makes this theory

00:16:29.424 --> 00:16:32.344
somewhat more compelling: it explains

00:16:32.344 --> 00:16:35.624
why children instinctively understand

00:16:35.644 --> 00:16:37.804
dragons without being taught.

00:16:38.704 --> 00:16:40.004
You don't have to explain

00:16:40.004 --> 00:16:42.354
to a child what a dragon is.

00:16:42.594 --> 00:16:44.444
You can show them a picture of a

00:16:44.444 --> 00:16:47.004
dragon, and even if they've never

00:16:47.084 --> 00:16:48.814
encountered the concept before,

00:16:49.424 --> 00:16:51.484
most children will understand

00:16:51.494 --> 00:16:53.594
immediately that it's dangerous,

00:16:53.844 --> 00:16:55.924
powerful, something to be feared.

00:16:57.144 --> 00:16:59.304
This suggests that the dragon

00:16:59.544 --> 00:17:01.244
might be tapping into something

00:17:01.694 --> 00:17:03.644
primal in our psychology.

00:17:04.214 --> 00:17:05.604
An archetype.

00:17:05.954 --> 00:17:09.134
A universal symbol of predatory threat.

00:17:09.504 --> 00:17:10.824
The monster that our

00:17:10.854 --> 00:17:12.724
ancestors feared in the dark.

00:17:13.869 --> 00:17:17.929
But again, even if this were true, it only

00:17:17.929 --> 00:17:20.619
goes part of the way to explaining things.

00:17:21.069 --> 00:17:24.579
Even if our brains are wired to fear

00:17:24.599 --> 00:17:27.299
dragon-like predators, this still

00:17:27.309 --> 00:17:29.309
doesn't fully explain the stories we

00:17:29.309 --> 00:17:32.719
tell about them—why dragons hoard gold,

00:17:33.039 --> 00:17:35.979
demand virgins, or represent chaos.

00:17:37.189 --> 00:17:39.029
For that, we need to talk

00:17:39.039 --> 00:17:41.229
about dragons as symbols.

00:17:42.439 --> 00:17:45.969
Because dragons were never just animals,

00:17:46.139 --> 00:17:48.409
even when people believed they were real.

00:17:48.879 --> 00:17:51.009
They were always symbols.

00:17:51.019 --> 00:17:52.729
Symbols of chaos.

00:17:52.939 --> 00:17:54.499
Of nature's power.

00:17:54.899 --> 00:17:55.689
Of greed.

00:17:56.109 --> 00:17:56.899
Of knowledge.

00:17:56.899 --> 00:17:58.259
Of transformation.

00:17:59.769 --> 00:18:02.589
In many ancient myths, dragons

00:18:02.949 --> 00:18:06.599
represented primordial chaos—the forces

00:18:06.599 --> 00:18:09.619
that existed before the ordered world.

00:18:10.339 --> 00:18:13.179
In Babylonian mythology, the god

00:18:13.179 --> 00:18:16.589
Marduk kills Tiamat, the dragon of

00:18:16.589 --> 00:18:20.049
saltwater and chaos, and from her corpse

00:18:20.269 --> 00:18:22.109
creates the heavens and the earth.

00:18:22.589 --> 00:18:24.539
The act of killing the dragon

00:18:24.929 --> 00:18:27.779
literally creates order from chaos.

00:18:28.455 --> 00:18:31.145
This pattern repeats across cultures.

00:18:31.545 --> 00:18:34.575
The hero kills the dragon, and in

00:18:34.585 --> 00:18:37.085
doing so, brings order to the world.

00:18:37.805 --> 00:18:40.325
Apollo kills the Python and

00:18:40.335 --> 00:18:42.419
establishes his oracle at Delphi.

00:18:43.089 --> 00:18:44.625
Saint George kills the

00:18:44.625 --> 00:18:46.405
dragon and saves the town.

00:18:46.735 --> 00:18:49.995
Beowulf kills the dragon and dies a hero.

00:18:50.455 --> 00:18:53.865
The dragon is the obstacle that must be

00:18:53.885 --> 00:18:56.755
overcome for civilisation to flourish.

00:18:57.665 --> 00:19:01.535
But dragons also represent other things.

00:19:02.595 --> 00:19:05.375
In many legends, dragons hoard

00:19:05.435 --> 00:19:07.785
treasure—specifically gold.

00:19:09.005 --> 00:19:09.435
Why?

00:19:10.145 --> 00:19:13.205
Well, gold in mythology often

00:19:13.225 --> 00:19:15.725
represents more than just wealth.

00:19:16.245 --> 00:19:18.155
It represents knowledge,

00:19:18.615 --> 00:19:20.339
power, immortality.

00:19:21.239 --> 00:19:23.279
The dragon guarding treasure is

00:19:23.279 --> 00:19:24.929
the dragon guarding knowledge

00:19:25.139 --> 00:19:26.789
that humans aren't ready for.

00:19:27.639 --> 00:19:31.139
To claim the treasure, the hero must prove

00:19:31.139 --> 00:19:33.809
himself worthy by defeating the dragon.

00:19:35.319 --> 00:19:38.099
In Christian symbolism, dragons became

00:19:38.119 --> 00:19:41.809
explicitly associated with Satan and evil.

00:19:42.479 --> 00:19:45.639
The dragon was paganism, the old

00:19:45.639 --> 00:19:48.049
gods, the forces of darkness.

00:19:48.709 --> 00:19:51.049
Saint George slaying the dragon was

00:19:51.069 --> 00:19:53.369
Christianity conquering paganism.

00:19:53.639 --> 00:19:56.829
It was good triumphing over evil.

00:19:57.039 --> 00:19:59.729
It was the new order replacing the old.

00:20:00.889 --> 00:20:03.319
But, you may well be thinking, this

00:20:03.339 --> 00:20:04.919
might make sense if we’re talking about

00:20:04.919 --> 00:20:08.229
the archetype of the bad, evil dragon.

00:20:08.779 --> 00:20:10.699
But what about the East Asian

00:20:10.699 --> 00:20:12.309
traditions of the good dragons,

00:20:12.329 --> 00:20:14.889
the dragons that help and provide?

00:20:15.749 --> 00:20:17.749
Well, here’s an interesting

00:20:17.749 --> 00:20:20.159
theory put forward by a man

00:20:20.199 --> 00:20:21.969
named Professor Ronald Hutton.

00:20:23.249 --> 00:20:26.169
In Europe, by the time humans

00:20:26.169 --> 00:20:27.929
were creating legends about

00:20:27.929 --> 00:20:30.899
things like dragons, humans faced

00:20:30.919 --> 00:20:32.869
no real threats from predators.

00:20:33.139 --> 00:20:35.259
Not giant snakes or leopards.

00:20:35.579 --> 00:20:39.359
And humans like to have large predators

00:20:39.359 --> 00:20:41.349
to tell stories about, predators

00:20:41.659 --> 00:20:43.619
who get killed by brave knights.

00:20:44.529 --> 00:20:46.139
In Europe, we had none,

00:20:46.599 --> 00:20:48.259
so we created dragons.

00:20:48.939 --> 00:20:52.099
In China, however, there was a large

00:20:52.129 --> 00:20:54.989
predator in the form of the tiger, which

00:20:55.159 --> 00:20:58.609
would kill humans and was very scary, so

00:20:58.799 --> 00:21:01.509
the Chinese had no need to create another.

00:21:02.409 --> 00:21:04.429
And therefore Chinese dragons

00:21:04.649 --> 00:21:06.929
became wise and benevolent.

00:21:08.049 --> 00:21:10.559
Now, you might be thinking, “ok, so

00:21:10.739 --> 00:21:13.429
people told stories about dragons, but

00:21:13.609 --> 00:21:16.529
did they actually believe in them? And

00:21:16.529 --> 00:21:19.069
if so, when did we stop believing?”

00:21:19.969 --> 00:21:22.049
The answer is: yes they did,

00:21:22.479 --> 00:21:24.289
and surprisingly recently.

00:21:25.459 --> 00:21:28.199
In medieval Europe, dragons were

00:21:28.199 --> 00:21:30.909
included in bestiaries—books that

00:21:30.989 --> 00:21:33.399
catalogued animals and their properties.

00:21:34.279 --> 00:21:36.859
These bestiaries listed dragons

00:21:36.889 --> 00:21:39.139
right alongside elephants,

00:21:39.279 --> 00:21:40.679
lions, and crocodiles.

00:21:41.269 --> 00:21:43.929
There was no distinction between "real"

00:21:43.929 --> 00:21:47.079
animals and "mythological" ones, because

00:21:47.309 --> 00:21:50.529
to medieval people, dragons were real.

00:21:51.199 --> 00:21:52.919
They were rare, certainly.

00:21:53.239 --> 00:21:53.949
Dangerous.

00:21:54.459 --> 00:21:55.199
Hard to find.

00:21:55.559 --> 00:21:56.759
But real.

00:21:57.809 --> 00:22:00.659
Medieval maps are often believed to

00:22:00.659 --> 00:22:03.149
have marked unexplored regions with

00:22:03.149 --> 00:22:05.819
the phrase "Here be dragons", although

00:22:05.839 --> 00:22:08.339
interestingly, this phrase appears

00:22:08.339 --> 00:22:10.929
on very few actual historical maps.

00:22:11.019 --> 00:22:12.799
So it's mostly a modern

00:22:12.809 --> 00:22:14.639
myth about medieval maps.

00:22:15.249 --> 00:22:18.799
But the sentiment was real: the edges

00:22:18.819 --> 00:22:21.219
of the known world were dangerous,

00:22:21.729 --> 00:22:24.539
mysterious, possibly full of dragons.

00:22:25.679 --> 00:22:28.659
Yet, as European explorers began

00:22:28.669 --> 00:22:31.875
mapping the world in the 15th, 16th,

00:22:31.875 --> 00:22:34.559
and 17th centuries, the spaces where

00:22:34.559 --> 00:22:37.269
dragons could exist began shrinking.

00:22:38.139 --> 00:22:40.299
Explorers sailed to the Americas.

00:22:40.619 --> 00:22:41.329
No dragons.

00:22:41.609 --> 00:22:42.999
They mapped the coast of Africa.

00:22:43.459 --> 00:22:44.239
No dragons.

00:22:44.549 --> 00:22:45.659
They travelled to Asia,

00:22:45.699 --> 00:22:47.229
to the Pacific islands.

00:22:47.549 --> 00:22:48.299
No dragons.

00:22:49.089 --> 00:22:51.469
By the 18th century, educated

00:22:51.469 --> 00:22:53.249
people were growing sceptical.

00:22:53.916 --> 00:22:56.224
The Age of Enlightenment brought a more

00:22:56.374 --> 00:22:59.014
scientific approach to the natural world.

00:22:59.841 --> 00:23:02.576
Carolus Linnaeus created his system of

00:23:02.686 --> 00:23:06.116
taxonomy, classifying all known animals.

00:23:06.826 --> 00:23:08.886
Dragons didn't make the list.

00:23:10.076 --> 00:23:12.126
And then, in the 19th century,

00:23:12.436 --> 00:23:13.986
came a revolution in our

00:23:14.046 --> 00:23:15.656
understanding of the past.

00:23:16.736 --> 00:23:19.506
Paleontology emerged as a science.

00:23:20.116 --> 00:23:22.526
People began correctly identifying

00:23:22.546 --> 00:23:25.316
fossilised bones as extinct animals:

00:23:25.846 --> 00:23:28.844
dinosaurs, mammoths, giant sloths.

00:23:29.794 --> 00:23:32.454
Suddenly, we had an explanation for

00:23:32.454 --> 00:23:34.884
the mysterious giant bones people

00:23:34.894 --> 00:23:36.394
had been finding for millennia.

00:23:37.244 --> 00:23:38.394
They weren't dragons.

00:23:38.884 --> 00:23:41.024
They were animals that had died millions

00:23:41.024 --> 00:23:44.014
of years ago, long before humans existed.

00:23:45.364 --> 00:23:48.194
Then, when Charles Darwin published On

00:23:48.194 --> 00:23:51.284
the Origin of Species in 1859, there

00:23:51.284 --> 00:23:53.634
was a framework for understanding

00:23:53.774 --> 00:23:55.954
how life on Earth had evolved.

00:23:56.934 --> 00:23:59.334
And by the end of the 19th century,

00:23:59.644 --> 00:24:02.174
dragons had been firmly relegated

00:24:02.404 --> 00:24:04.124
to the realm of mythology.

00:24:05.014 --> 00:24:08.374
But, perhaps funnily enough, this shift

00:24:08.384 --> 00:24:12.184
from the “scary but real” to the “a good

00:24:12.184 --> 00:24:14.364
source for myths and stories” propelled

00:24:14.374 --> 00:24:17.494
dragons to new heights, and they started

00:24:17.494 --> 00:24:19.354
to appear much more frequently in

00:24:19.354 --> 00:24:22.524
stories, in books and then in films.

00:24:23.904 --> 00:24:26.924
J.R.R. Tolkien loved dragon mythology

00:24:27.134 --> 00:24:29.564
as a child, and dragons feature

00:24:29.564 --> 00:24:32.074
prominently in his fantasy worlds.

00:24:32.904 --> 00:24:35.634
And most recently, Game of Thrones

00:24:35.644 --> 00:24:38.144
brought dragons back into mainstream

00:24:38.194 --> 00:24:40.444
popular culture in a massive way.

00:24:41.494 --> 00:24:43.524
So, to wrap things up, we

00:24:43.524 --> 00:24:45.044
haven't abandoned dragons.

00:24:45.374 --> 00:24:47.314
If anything, we've embraced them

00:24:47.474 --> 00:24:49.104
more enthusiastically than ever.

00:24:50.064 --> 00:24:50.544
Why?

00:24:51.094 --> 00:24:53.664
Well, perhaps because dragons fulfill

00:24:53.664 --> 00:24:55.914
a psychological need that facts

00:24:55.914 --> 00:24:58.344
and science can't quite satisfy.

00:24:59.044 --> 00:25:01.904
Dragons represent the ultimate challenge.

00:25:01.944 --> 00:25:04.524
The ultimate obstacle to overcome.

00:25:05.334 --> 00:25:07.864
When you defeat a dragon in a game,

00:25:07.874 --> 00:25:10.684
or read about a hero slaying a dragon,

00:25:10.994 --> 00:25:13.104
you're not just enjoying a story.

00:25:13.514 --> 00:25:15.374
You're engaging with an archetype

00:25:15.724 --> 00:25:17.004
that resonates with something

00:25:17.014 --> 00:25:18.784
deep in human psychology.

00:25:19.304 --> 00:25:21.934
The dragon is the fear you must face.

00:25:22.074 --> 00:25:24.284
The challenge that seems impossible.

00:25:24.524 --> 00:25:27.214
The transformation you must undergo

00:25:27.564 --> 00:25:28.994
to become who you're meant to be.

00:25:30.034 --> 00:25:31.654
And perhaps that's why dragons

00:25:31.674 --> 00:25:33.204
appear in every culture.

00:25:33.864 --> 00:25:35.984
Not because ancient people found

00:25:36.024 --> 00:25:38.104
dinosaur bones, though they did.

00:25:38.724 --> 00:25:40.464
Not because they encountered

00:25:40.464 --> 00:25:42.854
large reptiles, though they did.

00:25:43.434 --> 00:25:44.854
But because the dragon

00:25:45.094 --> 00:25:47.034
represents something fundamental

00:25:47.314 --> 00:25:48.834
about the human experience.

00:25:49.264 --> 00:25:51.394
The struggle against chaos.

00:25:51.544 --> 00:25:53.484
The fight against our fears.

00:25:53.744 --> 00:25:55.594
The journey from ordinary

00:25:55.594 --> 00:25:56.644
to extraordinary.

00:25:57.594 --> 00:25:59.654
Dragons never existed.

00:25:59.914 --> 00:26:01.994
But in a sense, they've always

00:26:01.994 --> 00:26:04.114
existed, and they always will.

00:26:04.664 --> 00:26:06.834
Not in caves or mountains

00:26:06.834 --> 00:26:08.094
or the depths of the sea.

00:26:08.504 --> 00:26:10.064
But in here.

00:26:10.204 --> 00:26:11.114
In our stories.

00:26:11.444 --> 00:26:12.624
In our imaginations.

00:26:13.204 --> 00:26:15.174
And perhaps that's the only

00:26:15.174 --> 00:26:17.114
place they ever needed to be.

00:26:18.904 --> 00:26:21.954
OK then, that is it for today's episode on

00:26:22.004 --> 00:26:24.664
dragons, the creatures that never existed

00:26:25.054 --> 00:26:27.124
but that every culture imagined anyway.

00:26:27.724 --> 00:26:29.414
And that brings us to the end

00:26:29.434 --> 00:26:31.104
of this three-part mini-series

00:26:31.324 --> 00:26:33.094
on animals throughout history.

00:26:33.324 --> 00:26:35.704
We've covered the loyal dog, the enigmatic

00:26:35.754 --> 00:26:38.824
cat, and the mythical dragon—three very

00:26:38.824 --> 00:26:41.034
different relationships between humans

00:26:41.244 --> 00:26:43.834
and animals, three very different stories.

00:26:44.264 --> 00:26:45.644
I hope you've enjoyed this journey

00:26:45.884 --> 00:26:47.574
through history, mythology,

00:26:47.734 --> 00:26:49.554
and evolutionary psychology.

00:26:50.194 --> 00:26:51.844
As always, you’ve been listening

00:26:51.864 --> 00:26:53.564
to English Learning for Curious

00:26:53.564 --> 00:26:55.494
Minds by Leonardo English.

00:26:55.964 --> 00:26:58.594
I'm Alastair Budge, you stay safe, and

00:26:58.594 --> 00:27:00.764
I'll catch you in the next episode.

